  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "The evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation has been significant, with key milestones including:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- Initial focus on reporting cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. 1980s-1990s Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Increased international collaboration\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n\n3. Post-9/11 Changes\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stricter regulations\n- Enhanced terrorist financing prevention\n- Greater information sharing between agencies\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Broader corporate transparency requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Advanced technological surveillance methods\n\n5. Global Standardization\n- More consistent international AML frameworks\n- Risk-based approaches\n- Comprehensive beneficial ownership disclosure\n- Expanded predicate offenses\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- AI-powered transaction monitoring\n- Blockchain tracking\n- Advanced data analytics\n- Real-time risk assessment capabilities\n\nLegislation continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
